    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The concept of a morally defensible position in this debate is inherently tied to the foundational principles of the nation itself, which is why strong arguments exist for both sides. The argument for national sovereignty and border security is morally grounded in the right of a government to control its borders and protect its citizens' safety and resources. Conversely, the humanitarian argument is morally grounded in universal human rights, asserting a duty to aid those fleeing persecution. Ultimately, a strong moral framework must prioritize the established law and the security of the existing society while still acknowledging the ethical obligations to vulnerable individuals.",
